2)

Make a frequency contingency table of dictator and level of freedom. Be sure to add the margins to the table, that is, the totals.

addmargins(table(Countries$dictator, Countries$fh)) %>% kable()
1. Free 2. Partly Free 3. Not Free Sum
0. Democracy 80 27 2 109
1. Dictatorship 7 26 46 79
Sum 87 53 48 188

3)

Do the same as above, but with the conditional proportions or percentages (also called conditional distributions).

addmargins(prop.table(table(Countries$dictator, Countries$fh))) %>% round(3) %>% kable

0. Democracy 0.426 0.144 0.011 0.58

Association: One Categorical, One Numerical Variable

A side-by-side box plot is useful way of graphing the relationship between a categorical variable and a numeric continuous variable. To do this you want to run separate box plots of the continuous variable for each value or group of the categorical variable.

A linear regression can be used for prediction. In particular, if you know values on the independent variable(s), you can predict the value for the dependent variable. Let’s say you were chatting with a friend who was a university student and she told you that she spent 9.5 hours per week, on average, studying for each course. Based on this information and your results from Question ##15, predict this student’s GPA.

x <- 9.5

categorical <- POL201 %>% select(-one_of(nums))
fisher.test(x = categorical$survey, y = categorical$gender)$p.value

x<-combn(x = names(categorical), m = 2, FUN = function(x) {
  fisher.test(x = categorical[,x[1]], y = categorical[,x[2]], workspace = 400000, simulate.p.value=TRUE)$p.value
  })

results <- combn(x = names(categorical), m = 2) %>% t %>% cbind(x) %>% as_data_frame() %>% setNames(c("one", "two", "pvalue")) %>% arrange(pvalue) %>% filter(pvalue < 0.01)

Plot associated categories

plot_categories <- function(one, two) {
  # one="gender"; two="toy"
  heatmap <- POL201[,c(one, two, "gpa")] %>% filter(!is.na(gpa)) %>% .[complete.cases(.),]
  # %>% group_by(party, party.close) %>% summarize(gpa = mean(gpa))
  
  p <- heatmap %>%
    ggplot(aes_q(x= as.name(one), fill = as.name(two))) +
    geom_bar(position="fill") +
    theme_bw()
  return(p)
}

for (i in 1:nrow(results)) {
  plot_categories(one=results$one[i], two=results$two[i]) %>% print
}
